### 2. Next-Generation Wireless Backhaul Design for Rural Areas
* **Slides**: [Next-Generation Wireless Backhaul Design for Rural Areas](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-gaia-next-generation-wireless-backhaul-design-for-rural-areas-00)
* **Presenter**: Leonardo Maccari
* **Technical Details**: 
  * Leonardo presented research on modeling the physical and economic feasibility of mesh-based wireless backhaul in underserved regions.
  * The study utilized 3D line-of-sight topographical models computed via GPUs across 10 rural Italian municipalities.
  * Evaluated equipment profiles included 5 GHz 802.11ac and 60 GHz 802.11ad devices, factoring in path loss models to calculate link capacity based on distance.
  * The economic model calculated CapEx (amortized over 5 years for wireless, 15 years for fiber) and OpEx (wholesale capacity, transport, maintenance, power) across various user penetration rates (25%, 50%, 100%). Results showed a monthly cost per subscriber ranging from €30 to €60, which was highly comparable to local DSL and satellite rates.
* **Q&A**:
  * **Kurtis Heimerl** questioned whether selecting the gateway node based on minimizing fiber-roll distance (the most expensive step) instead of topological centrality would yield better economic optimization. Leonardo noted that topological centrality reduces hop-count and link-capacity constraints, but optimizing purely for fiber length remains a valuable alternative.
  * **Alistair Woodman** observed that the estimated costs show why commercial telcos rationally ignore rural areas without receiving public subsidies, as density is too low to prove cost-effective.
  * **Leandro Navarro** asked how the market pricing has changed since the paper's initial data collection. Leonardo noted that hardware costs have decreased, but public infrastructure investments in these areas remain stagnant.
  * **Kurtis Heimerl** commented on the impact of Starlink on Wireless ISPs (WISPs), noting that many rural users choose Starlink over local WISPs due to perceived corporate reliability.
  * **Bill Baraza** asked about the specific hardware vendors simulated. Leonardo confirmed they used specifications modeled on Ubiquiti and MikroTik hardware planning platforms.

