### 5. Open Fiber Data Standard (OFDS)
* **Presenter**: Steve Song
* **Technical Details**:
  * Steve presented on the Open Fiber Data Standard (OFDS), an open-source structured data language designed to describe terrestrial fiber optic network layouts.
  * Because terrestrial operators often treat network maps as proprietary secrets, the OFDS project has built tools to crowdsource and standardize this geographic information.
  * He demonstrated a tool pipeline that:
    1. Imports static PNG/JPEG maps as image overlays into Google Earth to trace routes into KML files.
    2. Converts KML files into structured OFDS-compliant JSON and GeoJSON files while embedding metadata (owner, lease status, fiber strands, aerial/underground status).
    3. Uses "OFDS Studio", a custom plugin for the open-source QGIS application, to manage and visualizes these datasets.
    4. Automatically updates a global, collaborative, crowdsourced fiber map hosted on GitHub.
* **Q&A and Chat Discussion**:
  * **Dan York** shared a link to the [OFDS Hackathon GitHub repository](https://github.com/Open-Telecoms-Data/ofds-ietf-hackathon/) and highlighted the strength of the open-source [QGIS](https://qgis.org/) ecosystem.
  * **Kurtis Heimerl** asked if QGIS acts as an open-source ArcGIS (which Dan York confirmed) and why the standard focuses exclusively on fiber. Steve replied that fiber is the foundation of middle-mile transit, but the standard will expand to cover towers, aerial passive infrastructure, and FTTx.
  * **Leandro Navarro** shared Spain's Guifi.net experience, noting that transparent fiber mapping was legally vital for protecting community investments from predatory claims by commercial operators.
  * **John Levine** raised the security concern of making physical fiber routes discoverable to bad actors. Steve replied that the risk is minimal compared to the benefit; of the 10,000 annual fiber cuts in countries like Nigeria and Ghana, almost all are accidental civil works mistakes that could be prevented by having publicly accessible maps.

